notesStmt.note: Generally in good condition. First 3 folios and final folio are badly stained, some other folios show some water damage, a few of the miniatures have been damaged by water or deliberately defaced (for example, f. 156r, 247v).

msIdentifier.repository: Kislak Center for Special Collections, Rare Books and Manuscripts

msContents.summary: Vulgate Bible, with prologues for several books. Chapter divisions are generally more English or German than Parisian.

supportDesc.extent: 330 leaves : 375 x 246 (264 x 154) mm. bound to 400 x 280 mm
supportDesc.foliation: Parchment, 330; [1-330]; modern foliation in pencil, upper right recto.

layoutDesc.layout: Written in 2 columns of 56-58 lines, with illuminated border on the left edge of one or both columns on most pages.

scriptDesc.scriptNote: Written in a Gothic script, appears to be the work of a single scriptorium.

decoDesc.decoNote: Illuminated series of miniatures in a full-page initial at the beginning of Genesis, depicting the 7 days of Creation and the Crucifixion (f. 3v); historiated initials at the beginning of each subsequent book, a few integrated with an illuminated border; ornamented capitals, many with animals or animal faces in gold, rose, blue, red, and other colors on nearly every page; drolleries with animals and grotesques throughout.

binding.p: 18th- or 19th-century pigskin with oak boards and the remains of clasps.

origin.p: Possibly written and illuminated in Arras, France, in the last quarter of the 13th century.

history.provenance: Presented by Catherine and Thomas Coleman (1598-1647; f. 151r, 250r, 259r) to Ellis Fitzpatrick (f. 250r, 329r); William Farrell (f. 329r); T. Edward Ross (bookplate inside front cover).
